@tornadomeet Thank you for your answer!
I have see that we can change the code in the function named `read_list` definded in the `/mxnet/tools/im2rec.py`which can support the float label.
But I run the program failed.So I use `/mxnet/bin/im2rec` to transform my data but I don't know whether this program support the float type label.

@piiswrong  Do you mean `min_random_scale` and `max_random_scale` in ImageRecordIter? i had used it to train resnet-v2 on imagent, i think there is a little difference with using `min_size` and `max_size` done in the `im2rec` side, say that  we want to random resize the short edge to [256, 480], which is the default scale augment done in VGG, Resnet-v1, Resnet-v2.  
-  if set`resize=256` in `im2rec`, then the short edge is resized to 256, and this will bring in information losing( when the short edge is larger than 256 ). so if we set `min_random_scale=1.0` and `max_random_scale=480/256`, it is sure that the short edge is random with [256, 480], but it need resize again from the information losing roi.  
- if set `unchanged=1` in `im2rec`, then the information is perfect retained, but the vale of `min_random_scale` and `max_random_scale` is dynamic changed. another, this will make the size .rec file too large.

@piiswrong 
I don't think it is the problem. I test my work on cpu. In the first several iterations, the asnumpy cost about 6s. However, after 50 iterations, I waited for about twenty minutes. And the time cost of "forward" "backward" "update(weight)" is not increasing significantly.

And there's another problem now.  I set the num of iterations equals 1. After the iteration finished, the program can't quit. And the memory seemed not be released and continuously  occupied until it is eat up.

@sxjscience I am changing it to:

```
Assign(grad_weight, req[leakyrelu::kGamma], sumall_except_dim<1>(F<prelu_grad>(data) * grad));
Assign(gdata, req[leakyrelu::kData], F<mshadow_op::xelu_grad>(output, broadcast<1>(weight, data.shape_)) * grad);
```

The gamma of prelu is still growing to very large values. 

The above place should not be the reason for the divergence of the gamma values, as the default is "write" gradreq, and it will not affect the results.
